==Old English==
===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'næjel/
===Etymology===
Common Germanic *''[[naglaz]]'', from Indo-European ''*(o)nogh-''.

''Germanic cognates:'' Old Frisian [[neil]], Old Saxon [[nagal]] (Dutch [[nagel]]), Old High German [[nagal]] (German [[Nagel]]), Old Norse [[nagl]] (Swedish [[nagel]]).

''Indo-European cognates:'' Greek [[ονυχ]], Latin [[unguis]] (Italian [[unghia]], Spanish [[uña]]), Old Irish [[ingen]] (Breton [[ivin]], Cornish [[euuin]]), Slavic ''*nogъtь'' (Russian [[ноготь]]), Baltic ''*naga-'' (Lithuanian [[nagas|nãgas]]).

===Noun===
'''næġel''' ''m''
# the [[nail]] of a finger or toe
#:''Gif nægl of honda weorðe...'': if a nail comes off a hand... (''AS Leechbook'')
# a [[nail]] or [[peg]] as a fastening
#:''Mid næglum þurh-drifan ða hwitan honda'': the white hands were driven through with nails.  (''Exeter Book'')
# an instrument used to play the strings of a harp, a [[plectrum]]

